        <Document ID="9B64E500-9A8D-4994-BE7F-54CBBF107C26">
            <Title>Comic Script Format</Title>
            <Text>COMIC SCRIPT FORMAT
Contributed by Antony Johnson

About This Template
When compiled (File &gt; Compile), this project will generate a script suitable for comics and graphic novels. There is no industry standard for comic scripting, so this template was created by comics writer Antony Johnston, based on his earlier Final Draft template:

http://antonyjohnston.com/resources/samplescripts.php

Antony has also written an article for his website, demonstrating how he uses Scrivener and this template:

http://antonyjohnston.com/resources/scriveningcomics.php

Antonyâs original Final Draft template was designed in partnership with Andy Diggle, whose own template could equally serve as a basis for your own Scrivener comic script format:

http://andydiggle.blogspot.com/2006/07/final-draft-for-comics.html

Or, you could create an entirely new template that fits the way you work, using Format &gt; Script Settingsâ¦ to completely customise the script template.

How To Use This Template

Title Page
	â¢	A document entitled âTitle Pageâ can be found in the âFront Matterâ folder. This is used to hold the title, by-line and your name and address. Be sure to change the information in this document as appropriate.

Story Pages
	â¢	Pages are represented by text documents in the âDraft 1â folder. Upon compile for export or print, a page break is inserted between them.
	â	Note that the âDraft 1â folder is what we refer to in the documentation as the âDraft folderâ. A number has been appended for use in headers during Compile - see below.
	â¢	Each âPageâ can contain numerous panels, followed by the description text and dialogue for that panel.
	â¢	To create new pages, one way is to go to the Projects menu and select New From Template &gt; Comic Page. The new, blank page will appear immediately below the current Binder selection. You can also click and hold the green âAddâ toolbar button to select the âComic Pageâ document type, or hit Shift-Opt-Cmd-N on the keyboard. However, the easiest way is to click âAddâ or hit Cmd-N - while the focus is in the âComic Scriptâ folder, new documents created will automatically be based on the âComic Pageâ template (which can be found in the âTemplatesâ folder). This is because the âComic Scriptâ folder is set to use the âComic Pageâ template as its default document type (this has been set via Documents &gt; Default Template for Subdocuments).

Compiling
To compile, go to File &gt; Compile and ensure that âComic Scriptâ is selected in the list of formats on the left.

Page Headers
	â¢	Page headers use the settings in the Metadata pane of Compile, which can be accessed by clicking the tag icon above the contents list on the right of the Compile panel. Be sure to set the title of the project and writer name there.
	â¢	Page headers also display a draft number. This is taken from the title of the Draft folder. In a new project, this is âDraft 1â. Be sure to change the title of the Draft folder if you wish to increment the draft number.

About the Styles Used
	â¢	This template contains the most common styles used for comics: Page Number, Panel Number, Panel Description, Character, Dialogue and Parenthetical.
	â¢	Page Number appears only once for each page, at the top of the document. Pressing TAB after typing will insert the &lt;$N&gt; character string, which will be replaced with sequential numbering upon compile and so allows you to auto-number your pages.
	â¢	Panel Number is used to denote a single panel of comic art on the page. Press TAB after typing to insert the &lt;$sn&gt; string, which will auto-number your panels within each page during the Compile process. Press ENTER to automatically put the text into Panel Description mode.
	â¢	Panel Description is used to describe the image within each panel of art. Multiple paragraphs of Panel Description text can be used in a panel description. Therefore, press ENTER after typing to keep the text in Panel Description mode. To enter Character mode, press TAB either after typing, or while on a blank line.
	â¢	Character denotes a speaking character within a panel, and precedes their dialogue. Press ENTER to put the text into Dialogue mode. Press TAB to make notes on lettering style for the dialogue that follows, e.g. âLargeâ, âSmallâ, âJaggedâ, or âOffâ (useful for when a speaking character is not visible in panel). These notes are usually made in parentheses, so in this template a left parenthesis (i.e. the â(â character) is automatically inserted after the characterâs name, and the auto-complete library for this style contains text with closed parentheses. 
	â¢	Caption boxes are regarded as dialogue, and so âCAPTIONâ should be used in place of a character name, followed by the text to appear in the box.
	â¢	Sound effects are similarly denoted with âSFXâ.
	â¢	If a panel is completely silent (i.e. has no dialogue, caption or sound effect) then a character of âNO DIALOGUEâ should be entered, ending the panel.
	â¢	Dialogue is the speech of each character. Dialogue is not broken up into true paragraphs. Therefore, press ENTER to move the text back into Panel Description mode. If you wish to break a long section of dialogue into multiple balloons, press TAB to enter Parenthetical mode.
	â¢	Parenthetical is used to link together multiple dialogue balloons spoken by the same character in a single panel. Simply type âcontâ and hit either TAB or ENTER; parentheses will automatically be placed around the âcontâ text, and the text will return to Dialogue mode on a new line.
	â¢	Other lettering notes can also be made in the parentheticals after the âcontâ text, e.g. âcont, smallâ or âcont, jaggedâ. Lettering notes that affect the entire dialogue should be made on the Character line, as noted above.

Sample Document
See the âComic Scriptâ PDF file in the Research folder for an example of a document that has been created using this template, and to see a short sample of how a comic script using Antonyâs format should look.

Final Note
Scrivener project templates are flexible and are not intended to restrict you to a particular workflow. You can change, delete or move the files and folders contained in the template to suit how you work.

Like all templates in Scrivener, this project was originally created from the âBlankâ template. Weâve simply added a few folders and set everything up in ways that should be useful to comic script writers. Everything you can do with this project, you could equally do by creating a âBlankâ project and setting it up yourself.

You can create your own templates by setting up a skeletal project with the files, folders and settings you would like to use for new projects and using File &gt; Save As Template.

Thank you to Antony Johnston for contributing this template.</Text>
        </Document>
